After a lapse of three-score years, the same fondness still existed. The very defects of the old writers were carefully copied. A corrupt age is always an affected one: simplicity is lost in silliness; and vigour in preposterous tumour. Rude and ob- solete terms were culled from the old drama to gratify a morbid taste, a sickly delicacy which had no relish of nature, and to the indulgence of which the poet justly attributes the corruption of fo- rensic eloquence and the debility of metrical composition. qnid quod nihil jam proprium placet, dum parum cre- ditur disertum quod alius daverit? a corruptissimo quoque poetarum figuras seu translationes mutuamur, tum de- mum ingeniosi, si all intellzyemlos nos. opus sit ingenio!
